<p class="lead"><strong>When you enter information into a cell, you may need to change the size of a
row or column so that the information will be able to be seen.</strong></p class="lead">
	


<p>When you type data into a cell, you may notice that when you are
finished typing and press a key to take you to the next cell, you may not be
able to see all of the data in the cell anymore. Do not worry! The data you
typed is still in the cell, but hidden because the cell is too small to show all
of it. In order to show all of the data, you will need to size either the
column or the row.</p>

<p>To do this, move your cursor to the edge of a row or column heading.
Notice that your cursor changes shape when you do this. Then, click and drag
with your mouse to make the column or row the size that you want. The
entire column or row will adjust to the new width.</p>

<p>When entering numeric data into a cell, or when entering a formula, if you
see##### in a column, it means your column is too small. Click and drag with
your mouse to widen the column. When the column is wide enough, the #####s will
go away.</p>


<div class="row">
<div class="twelve columns">
<h4>Sizing a Column or a Row</h4>

<p>Sizing is the same for all versions of Excel.</p>

<p>In the worksheet below, notice that you cannot see all of the text in the
Columns or the Rows. Also notice in Column D, that many of theve ###### in them. This means D is too
narrow for the data to displayed.</p>


<img class="img-wrap style1" src="images/spreadsheets/sizingbefore.jpg" alt="">


<p>Take your cursor and place it on the edge of a row or column heading and
then click and drag to make the column or row bigger. Notice that cursor changes shape when you do this. It looks like a double arrow.</p>

<img class="img-wrap style1" src="images/spreadsheets/doublearrow.png" alt="">


<p>In the worksheet below, the user has widened Column A and all of the data can now be seen.
Column D has also been widened and the  ###### have disappeared.</p>


<img class="img-wrap style1" src="images/spreadsheets/sizingafter.jpg" alt="">


<p>If you cannot see all of the information in a cell, but you do not want to
size the column to make it wider, you can change the format in the cells for how
the data displays. You can do this by changing the alignment within the cell to
wrap text or by using the shrink to fit option. You learned how to access all
of these in the section on <strong>Formatting Cells</strong>.</p>

